The dal had been the same dal for four nights.

This was not a matter of opinion. Adarsh had documented it. On the first night he had noted the texture — slightly overcooked, with a thin, yellowish water pooling at the edge of the bowl where the lentils had separated from the liquid. On the second night, identical. On the third night, he had moved to a different table, wondering if the problem was geographical. It was not. On the fourth night, he brought the bowl from Tuesday and held it next to the bowl from Friday to compare.

They were, to a reasonable degree of culinary certainty, the same dal.

"This is not fresh dal," he said.

"No," Vicky agreed, eating it.

"He is reheating it."

"Probably."

"We are paying fourteen rupees a month for the meal plan."

"We are."

Adarsh looked at the bowl. Then at Vicky. "Someone should write a complaint."

"You should write one," Vicky said.

"You write better."

"I write the same as you."

"You write with more authority," Adarsh said.

This was not true, and they both knew it, but Vicky finished his dal, took a piece of paper from the folder in his bag, and wrote a complaint. He addressed it to the Warden's Office, Hostel Block C. He described the dal across four nights with a precision that would have impressed a pathology professor. He requested an investigation into the hostel kitchen. He signed it.

Then he looked at the signature for a moment. He crossed it out and wrote instead: *— The Dissection Table Committee.*

Adarsh looked at the paper. "There is no Dissection Table Committee."

"There is now," Vicky said. "We are it."

He folded the paper, walked down the corridor to the warden's room, and slid it under the door.

---

The warden, Mr. V.K. Srivastava, was a meticulous man who believed in the power of institutional process. He received the complaint the following morning, read it carefully, and noted that it raised legitimate concerns about food quality and hostel management standards.

He summoned the Dissection Table Committee to appear before him at four o'clock that afternoon.

At four o'clock, nobody came.

At four-fifteen, nobody came.

At four-thirty, Mr. Srivastava sent the hostel peon to find the Dissection Table Committee, with instructions to search the reading room first and the television room second. The peon returned at five o'clock and reported that he had searched both rooms, the ground floor corridor, the water filter area, and part of the botanical garden path, and had found no trace of any group identifying themselves as a committee of that name.

Srivastava consulted the hostel registration records. There was no Dissection Table Committee in any official list of student organizations, clubs, or groups.

He sent a notice to the class noticeboard: *The Dissection Table Committee is requested to present themselves to the warden's office at the earliest convenience.*

The notice stayed on the board for eleven days. Nobody came.

---

The cook made fresh dal the following Monday. It was, objectively, worse than the four-night dal. It had no cumin and too much water and a sourness that suggested the lentils had been an ambitious choice given what was available.

Vicky ate it without comment.

Adarsh ate two bites and set his spoon down. "The old dal was better."

"Yes," Vicky said.

"We have made things worse."

"Progress is frequently indistinguishable from its opposite in the short term," Vicky said. He was reading a chapter on thoracic anatomy. He ate the rest of his dal without putting the book down.

---

The Dissection Table Committee became part of the hostel's informal legend after that. The story improved with each retelling. By the end of second year, it had acquired a dramatic confrontation between the Committee and the warden, a petition with a hundred signatures, and an emergency meeting of the student union that had never actually taken place. The only accurate detail that survived across all versions was the name.

Adarsh kept the original complaint letter. He slid it into his Pathology textbook between pages 220 and 221, between the chapter on inflammatory lung disease and the chapter on cardiac pathology. He had not planned to keep it. He simply forgot it was there.

He found it again thirty years later, in the hospital, on a day when he needed something to do with his hands while he waited for news from an ICU room.

The letter had yellowed at the edges, and the ink had gone grey and thin. But Vicky's handwriting — which had been neat even then, the 'A' in Ahuja already sharp and clear — was still entirely legible.

At the bottom, the Dissection Table Committee had signed their name in full. It was the last formal record, in Vicky's handwriting, from before he left college. From before everything changed.

Adarsh read it twice. Then he closed the book.

[End of Section]
